	<pb n="0001" facs="liv_001240_0001"/><!--pb/@n='1r'-->
<lb/><p rend="right"><placeName>18 Hart St</placeName></p>
<lb/><p rend="right"><placeName>Bloomsbury</placeName></p>
<lb/><p rend="right">17 Feby 1858 </p>
<lb/><p>Dear Sir George </p>
<lb/><p>I am ashamed 
<lb/>of my manners 
<lb/>since my return 
<lb/>to <placeName>England</placeName>, I never 
<lb/>called nor thanked 
<lb/>you for your 
<lb/>kind gift, though 
<lb/>if you will only 

	<pb n="0002" facs="liv_001240_0002"/><!--pb/@n='1v'--> 
<lb/>believe me I shall 
<lb/>tell you how it is 
<lb/>I have appeared so 
<lb/>unnatural. The 
<lb/>first part of my 
<lb/>sojourn in <placeName>England</placeName>
<lb/>was so taken up 
<lb/>with the book - 
<lb/>the second with 
<lb/>the speechifying 
<lb/>and the third 
<lb/>with preparation 

	<pb n="0003" facs="liv_001240_0003"/><!--pb/@n='2r'--> 
<lb/>for leaving that 
<lb/>I must have seemed 
<lb/>to those who do not 
<lb/>make allowances 
<lb/>as decidedly wanting 
<lb/>in common 
<lb/>politeness<reg>.</reg> But 
<lb/>I can honestly say 
<lb/>that I deeply feel 
<lb/>the sympathy you 
<lb/>have manifested 
<lb/>for my work 
<lb/>and I thank you

	<pb n="0004" facs="liv_001240_0004"/><!--pb/@n='2v'-->
<lb/>most heartily for 
<lb/>the friendship which 
<lb/>you and <persName>Lady Back</persName>
<lb/>have shewn. If 
<lb/>ever I return you 
<lb/>will find me 
<lb/>a more natural man 
<lb/>than I have been 
<lb/>this time. If not 
<lb/>may we through 
<lb/>mercy meet each 
<lb/>other in Heaven<reg>.</reg></p>
<lb/><p rend="center">I am gratefully 
<lb/>yours</p>
<lb/><p rend="center"><persName>David Livingstone</persName></p>

